Given a coroutine body<p>```
int f()
{
    a;
    co_yield r;
    b;
    co_return r2;
}
```<p>this transforms into<p>```
auto f(auto then)
{
    a; 
    return then(r, [&amp;]()
    {
        b;
        return then(r2);
    });
};
```<p>You can easily extend this to arbitrarily complex statements. The main thing is that obviously, you have to worry about the capture lifetime yourself (coroutines allocate a frame separate from the stack), and the syntax causes nesting for every statement (but you can avoid that using operator overloading, like C++26&#x2F;29 does for executors)
